                <h2 class="AboutMe">
                  About Me
                </h2>
                <p class="two-text">
                  For the past three years I have been striving to get my bachelors of Computer Science at the Masters University. After I graduate I am currently planning on pursuing the <a target="_blank" href="https://jetprogramusa.org/">JET program</a>. JET stands for Japan Exchange and Teaching. The program is essentially a paid exchange program where college graduates go to teach in Japanese high schools for two to five years. Although moving to Japan out of college is a bold move, I find that because of my past experiences and current passions it is justified. Much of the reasons for choosing to pursue Computer Science and consider the JET program originated in high school. Currently I am semi-fluent in Chinese (fully fluent when I was in China). This passion of mine began freshmen year of high school. I chose to take Chinese instead of Spanish because I felt that it would provide more of a challenge and it was a unique language compared to what everyone takes. Two years later I took my first trip to China. During that trip, my passion for Asian languages and international travel grew greatly. Since then, I have traveled every summer. I have grown to appreciate the unique and enriching experiences of traveling. Travel has become the discovery and pursuit of culture. On top of my love for travel, I love creating. The first two years of high school I took video class, creating unique and fun videos. The next two years I dove into film photography, producing beautiful and compelling photos. I loved the amazing amount of creativity film allowed. Things took a turn my senior year of high school. I decided to move away from arts and dive into the technical and scientific world. I took a computer science class. By the first month of the class, I had already finished the course work for the entire year and decided to take the AP class. I finished the course work for the AP by the end of the winter. My desire to create was met with the infinite possibilities Computer Science allowed. Because of those desires, I find myself here. Absolutely loving the amazing and intricate word of Computer Science. With the skills that I have, I look to continue to learn everything I can. Enjoying each season of life, in all of its quirks.
                </p>
