              <div class="row" style="height: 84%;">
                <div class="col-md-12 scrollableText" style="height: 100%;">
                  <div>
                    <div class="row row-center row-no-margin" style="width: 100%;">
                      <div class="col-md-12" style="text-align:center;">
                        <h1 style="text-align:left;">Too much Fluff</h1>
                        <p>
                          Ever since high school I have had a bad habit of adding too much fluff into how I write. I struggle sometimes to get to the point. I tend to be too “thorough” with my explanations and lack the balance of brevity in my sentence order and structure. It maybe the case that even this explanation contains fluff and lacks the necessary brevity to keep a reader engaged. Nevertheless, I must be aware of these issues and attempt to repair and improve how I write. I must remember that a reader is trying to understand not to look at the size of my work and say good job. I think part of the reason I have struggled with fluff in essays past is due to the need to meet the minimum number of pages or words. I find myself focusing less on this than what point I am trying to make.
                        </p>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="row row-center row-no-margin" style="width: 100%;">
                      <div class="col-md-12" style="text-align:center;">
                        <h1 style="text-align:right;">Writer’s Block</h1>
                        <p>
                          One of the biggest challenges for me when attempting to write anything is assuring my undivided and uninterrupted focus on it. In other words, I get distracted quite easily. I find that my thoughts drift off the topic mid-sentence and must go back through the whole paragraph so that I can pick up where I left off. I cannot simply read the last sentence, and pick up where I left off. I need to remind myself of the context and make sure that I am staying true to the greater point I am making in that paragraph and essay. The thought of making every sentence tie in and add to the greater thesis of the essay a difficult exercise in writing. I tend to get stuck what I should or need to say next to accomplish my goal of completion. I find it especially difficult to write in high pressure situations because my mind easily drifts towards thinking about a specific issue that is dominating my mind. Overall, I have two solutions to alleviate my writers block. The first is getting up and doing something else for a bit and then revisiting the essay later to finish. The second is to find a way to be passionate about the topic of the essay. If I am passionate about something, it is difficult for me to shut up about the topic.
                        </p>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="row row-center row-no-margin" style="width: 100%;">
                      <div class="col-md-12" style="text-align:center;">
                        <h1 style="text-align:left;">Wording</h1>
                        <p>
                          Wording is a challenge in that I am always trying to find the best way to verbalize a certain feeling or idea, but I cannot remember the word or how to describe it. Descriptions are awesome tools in writing, but if not practiced and done well it tends to show off the poor quality of a writer much quicker than a very articulate and capable writer. I of course tend to be in the first camp. I like to use unique and impressive words that I would like others to think I know.
                        </p>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
